an argument is sound when it is valid and all of its premises are true
1. Either Notre Dame is in Indiana or Notre Dame is in Ohio.
2. Notre Dame is not in Ohio.
C. Notre Dame is in Indiana. (1,2)

Here is a third way to see why the argument is valid. The Venn diagram at left represents three ways the world could be. The first premise rules out the green possibilities. The second premise rules out the blue possibilities. So the premises rule out all but the red possibility, which is what the conclusion says.
